description.text: I have taken my previous design called The YABA and changed it into this design that I call Magnet YABA. The main difference is that this changes how the adapter attaches to the printer. This uses two press-fit magnets to hold the adapter onto the printer. To keep the extruder assembly together we use two printed spacers, allowing us to use the stock screws. I found the stock setup needed longer spacers than my custom setup that could use shorter spacers. There is only a 3mm length difference. I labeled all the files before uploading them.

Notes:

I use supports on the yaba, specifically where it bridges the fan input. I do that to keep anything like sagging at a minimal.

I print the spacers solid. I have had a set fail over time, so I recommend printing a few sets for backup. In case a set fails or you loose one when taking the extruder assembly apart.

Below is the hardware I used for this modification

  1. One M4 screw by 20mm length
  2. One M4 nut
  3. One 5015 or 50mm blower fan
  4. Two Magnets 8mm diameter by 4mm thick ( I did sized the holes up for 10mm diameter magnets because someone asked for it, but I have not tested it as I have 8mm diameter magnets) Going to link to the website where I got my magnets from. Feel free to try them from other places, I just know these work from using them. https://ultimate3dprintingstore.com/products/super-strong-magnets

This modification essentially splits the adapter and extruder assembly into two groups. This allows you to pull off and put the adapter back on without unscrewing the extruder assembly.
All the other pros of The YABA are still here in this version. This includes not having the fan blades near the screws that hold the extruder assembly together. Using a radial fan instead of an axial fan.

I use the stock screws in this design for a couple of reasons. Firstly it means less hardware needed. Secondly they are what the magnets are attracted to. Finally by using them with spacers we make the yaba always center onto the heat-sink and not simply slide off the side of the extruder assembly. I also did a video where I talked a bit about this design https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rTdIQBI9qcE

title: Alunar 508 Prusa i3 X&Z-Axis; Cable Chain

description.text:
This is my version of a combined X and Z-axis cable chain for the Alunar Prusa i3 printer.

The end on the extruder replaces the X-axis end stop mount. It provides a filament guide as well as moving the end stop switch in 10mm. This moves the end stop over an additional 10mm so the print bed can be pulled out without hitting the extruder on the binder clips used to hold the print surface down.

There is a piece on the left Z-axis guide that attaches using one of the stepper motor screws. It sneaks the wires through without affecting the Z-axis range.

The end of the second chain terminates on a mount that avoids hitting the X-axis stepper motor as it rises.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

I used 0.15 with a 0.3mm nozzle

Infill:

100%

Notes:

The chain links print OK without supports, you need a lot of them and you don't want to have to clean each one off. Lay them flat to print.

The X-axis end prints best with the wide end of the funnel pointing down with supports from the bed only.

The X-Z axis piece prints best sticking up on end with supports on all.

Assembly:

To make the chain, place the first piece on a flat surface and grab the second with the narrow end pointed out. Press it down firmly on the first one and the chamfer on the bottom will help it snap in place. I needed 30 links in the X-axis and 12 in the Z-axis. The thinner chain worked for the X-axis and I used the thicker one for the Z-Axis.

Look at the second picture for the placement of the mounting hole required for an M4 nut/bolt (My kit had spares). It should be about 1/2 way between the Z-axis stops and 6mm in.

Run the extruder wires through the chains (I used a loop of string to pull them one at a time). Don't forget the X-axis stepper motor ribbon cable.

Replace the X-axis zero stop with the new part, a cutout is provided for a cable strain relief strap. Attache the micro-switch (Don't forget to update your settings to account for the 10mm offset).

Mount the X to Z axis part using the upper right stepper motor bolt.

Mount the Z axis end to the chassis.

Run the wires through the guides and snap on the chains.

title: Emmett's Moineau Soap Dispenser - rescaled and thickened

description.text:
While I love Emmett's soap dispenser (and everything else the clever bugger does) I always had a few issues when printing it on one of my machines. My old Sells/Prusa Mendel hasn't quite got the build volume to print this at full size, and it often struggles with the inner face of the outer wall of the bottle - if that makes sense... This Rehash is a slight rescaling of the original to fit on my print bed - the rotor and bottle are now no taller than 95mm. All the parts were scaled down from Emmett's original by 84.82% I've also added a mod of the bottle, that just increases the wall thickness a tad - this makes it easier to get a nicely watertight print
The thicker walled body also has an upload at the same size as Emmetts original - in case anyone wants to use this with that. I'm debating thickening up the outer wall of the moineau cavity - if anyone needs that, let me know...

description.text:
A simple, but effective cable chain setup.

Print one X-AxisCableChainMount which can be attached directly to the top of x-axis plates that move the laser head around. For the other end of the chain you will have to drill a couple of holes to tie off the end of the cable chain. Use can use a 1/8" or 3.5 mm drill bit to cut these holes.

For the Y-AxisCableChainMount and Y-AxisCableChainMount-Leg print one of each normally, these will go on the left side of the frame. Then use your slicer to mirror these parts on one of the axis (as they are laid out, this would be on the x-axis) so that they can be installed on the right side of the machine.

You will need eight M3 nuts, eight 6 or 8mm M3 bolt/screws to install the cable chains end pieces. Additionally you'll need ten M4x12mm screws and nuts to install the mounts to the ACRO laser. You won't need to drill any M4 holes anyplace - I used existing holes for these.

You will need about 28 or 29 chains in your links for each side of the y-axis as well as the x-axis. Print two sets of the end pieces for one side of the y-axis as well as the x-axis. Then print another set using the mirror tool in your slicer for the right side of the y-axis.

description.text:
Yet another temperature calibration tower. It suppose to be smart, compact and fulfill several purposes.

  • it is functioning as a regular temperature tower
  • it contains several test patterns like
    • overhangs from 60 deg to 25 deg
    • bridges from 15 mm - 30 mm
    • stringing test
    • curvy shapes

One floor is exactly 10 mm and stand is 1.4 mm. Optimized for 0.2 mm layer height.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Correct temperatures have to be setup in the generated gcode.
It can be easily done in Slicr3d Prusa edition min. v 1.38.5

Printer Settings -> Custom G-code -> Before layer change G-code
correct macro needs to be setup. It should look like

{if layer_z==1.6}; T tower floor 1
M104 S250
{elsif layer_z==11.6} ...

It specifies different temperature for each temperature tower floor.

There are 2 txt files included in the project one for PLA and one for ABS towers with the correct macro.

  • ABS_t_tower_before_layer_change_macro.txt
  • PLA_t_tower_before_layer_change_macro.txt

Content can be easily copy pasted.

There are 2 complete temperature towers

  • PLA 180C - 225C
  • ABS 200C - 250C

These can be used as they are. Don't forget to setup correct temperatures. See the section above.

There are also separated modules for temp floors from 170C to 260C with 5C step and a stand. New heat tower can be easily combined out of them.

I started with 3d printing by may of 2017. I wanted to learn as much as possible in the shortest possible time and speed up configuration of my printer as much as possible. Print out long lasting temperature towers and then other testing shapes was too long to me. So I decided to create a new heat tower which is as compact as possible, serves many basic quality test purposes too and printing take as short time as possible.

I am using it as a basic temperature setup guidance for different filaments. It sped up my setups at least 3 - 4 times. One print instead of 3 - 5.

Currently I am bringing it to you. Enjoy it and I am looking forward to reading any feedback.

description.text:
Hi Internet Sim Racers!

Christmas is here, I'd managed to escape the kids for an hour and whipped up something I'd wanted to do for ... well, since last christmas....

LED Mini Torches are perfect for conversion to a smart looking Shift Light for your dirty sim racing habit!!

I got mine from Officeworks in Australia for $2.99AUD... Conveniently, the internal profile is large enough to fit a arduino pro micro (My favorite!).

So I decided to use a small pipe and hammer to punch out from the inside the original LED array. There is an aluminium step its pressed into see... so pull the battery out, push something solid in, and WHACK it with a hammer. It should pop right out!

Now, my models are designed to fit directly into the empty barrel. The lense is ~23.5mm which depending on your printer accuracy is close enough to wedge in nicely. The main body will push into the bottom of the lense with a little super glue to keep it in place with the lense.

I hot glued my RGB WB2812B LED on the top of the main barrel. It works, its simple... and despite the original version being much more elaborate. This just prints easier and you need to glue the LED anyway. so... y'know...

The base lock is optional. I found the arduino didn't slide around at all.

Oh and the switch in the bottom cover of the torch should just push through from the rubber end and pop out the inside. It's a press fit too. Just put a slot in the rubber button cover and push your USB micro lead through it and screw it on to finish it up.

The blue one I made was a really old torch and perfect for a test. My printer also had a blocked nozzle for the test print but it all fit okay together. I have little reservation about the model. Once I clean the nozzle of the printer it should be smooth again.

Have a go, the results are pretty neat.

Oh, and if you don't want to print a lense with transparent filament.... Get an old plastic Milk bottle.. and cut out a circle to push in over the LED. It'll work just as well.

description.text: Tired of your fingers hurting trying to use the stock folgertech thumbwheel for leveling? Try these for smooth as silk adjustments that are much more precise. Once printed take a soldering iron once hot and press the tip into the direct center of the threaded nut as seen in the photos and gently press.. As the nut warms up it will start to slide into the wheel.. once flush dont push any more but keep the heat on for a few more seconds to let the material flow into the knurled edges of the nut... let fully cool ( or put in cold water) before using. The alum nut should be face down when installing back to the printer. I also suggest a flat washer in between the wheel and the bed.

I've been wanting to try making fan blades for a while and this was the first one i made that I thought looked passable. Basically I'm uploading it more as a community project. I'd love to see how people fix and change this model to be better according to various requirements or aesthetic wants.

You can use it as a prop in a scene, you can print it, (but i didn't really design it to be printed so you may run into many issues) you can do anything, just make sure to tag me so i can see your changes :3

Notes:

i didn't put much thought into printing this so do so at your own peril.

In Blender i started with a plane and extruded out to the side. Each extrusion was rotated 5 degrees starting from 0. I repeated extruding and rotating until i got to 35 and then the last two sections that meet the outer ring went to 37 and 39 degrees. the one section i extruded to the nose cone was rotated -5 or -2 degrees, i can't remember which.

i added some edge loops and pulled some vertices and edges to try and smooth out the curves then added a subsurf.

Then i arrayed the wing and ended up at 9 repetitions.

For the nose cone and just tried to eyeball a surface that was some-what aero inspired.

i poofed into existence a cylinder mesh and scaled it accordingly around the perimeter of the blades.

I didn't join any thing into a singular piece in blender but slic3r and cura both sliced up the stl with no visual problem.

I haven't applied the array so you can fiddle with the blend file pretty heavily/easily
I don't believe i applied the subsurf's so the base shapes should still be fairly low poly still if your computer chugs on high poly stuff.

description.text:
Holder/Mount for GOPRO Session

Fusion 360 and Step file included.

I printed with supports at least for the big openings. But you might be able to get away without it if your printer is dialed.

Is this is what happens if you steam cauliflower in Mountain Dew using a microwave oven? No, it's something much more mundane: a tiny glowing nuclear mushroom cloud perfect for your desktop, locker or mantelpiece. The original detonated on Shapeways some time back and caused something of a stir mostly because of its outrageous price. MaximFilms made the T-verse version which you can print for significantly less than the cost of a used car. I wanted something which glows by itself so I boolean punched my 2032 led holder into the stalk et voila: radioactive cauliflower. The one pictured was printed in glow-in-the-dark yellow and illuminated with a UV led for best effect. As with anything you want to print to a precise size, the calibration of your printer is critical. I recommend printing just the bottom of the stalk first to make sure your battery fits before committing to a 12hr print. Also be forewarned that this sucker requires almost as much support material finished product so it is pretty wasteful. Printing upside down might reduce the waste a bit, but I haven't tried it. This thing was featured on the 3D Printing Today podcast available on iTunes, Stitcher radio or direct from the source at http://threedprintingtoday.libsyn.com/

description.text:
A quick hatchet job 1/4 inch to hot shoe adapter with a printed thread (the other one I found on here required a 1/4 inch nut which I didn't have on hand).

I've used this to adapt a small camera tripod (Fotopro FY-583) to hold a Rode Videomic Pro hot shoe. Assuming it should work with all Rode videomic models.

Should print in PLA with no support in the default orientation with no problems.

The thread for this design was borrowed from wizprods adapter (this part was a bit beyond my lowly Tinkercad skills), the rest was derived from basic measurements. Managed to get the part to work on my first prototype, could probably be refined more, but left as is as it got the job done!

The other printed thing in this photo is an mic extension cable tidy for Fotopro FY-583, which is a cheap 1m Tripod that makes for a great pairing with the Videomic, it can be set up quickly and packed away rather compact. Add a headphone extension cable (ie. 3.5mm mic) and you are good to go. Link to the cable tidy is here:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2729418

Disclaimer: Whilst care has been taken to make this part strong, I take no responsibility for the mount breaking or damaging any expensive hot shoe mounted gear you might own. Use entirely at your own risk.

title: Customizeable Fractal Snowflakes
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is my entry for the #BlocksCADSnowflake Challenge and was created using BlocksCAD (https://www.blockscad3d.com/).

Create your own custom snowflake by customizing this model! No snowflake is like the others.

The snowflake is based on a very simple fractal design with a deep of up to 3 branches. It can be controlled using the 12 variables declared at the beginning of the code. You can either use the BlocksCAD website and import the Customizeable_Fractal_Snowflakes.xml there or import the Customizeable_Fractal_Snowflakes.scad file into OpenSCAD.

The variables are:

  • Overall_Thickness: The height of the snowflake in z-Direction

  • Primary_Branches_Amount: The amount of primary branches which are circled around the center. Very large values can cause a slow Rendering due to the factal design.
  • Primary_Branches_Length: The length of the primary braches from the origin.

  • Primary_Branches_Thickness: The width of the primary branches

  • Secondary_Branches_Distance: The distance between two secondary braches. Low values can cause the branches to overlap.
  • Secondary_Branches_Angle: The angle between the secondary branches and perpendicular to the corresponding primary branch. 0° means primary and secondary branch being perpendicular.
  • Secondary_Branches_Thickness: The width of the secondary branches

  • Secondary_Branches_Length_Scale: The default length of the secondary branches is their distance from the origin. This scale factor is applied on that.

  • Tertiary_Branches_Distance: The distance between two tertiary braches.
  • Tertiary_Branches_Angle: The angle between the tertiary branches and perpendicular to the corresponding secondary branch. 0° means secondary and tertiary branch being perpendicular.
  • Tertiary_Branches_Thickness: The width of the tertiary branches.
  • Tertiary_Branches_Length_Scale: The default length of the tertiary branches is their distance from their secondary branch. This scale factor is applied on that.

There are no restrictions on the parameter. The sky is the limit.
If you dont want secondary or tertiary branches to be generated, just set the corresponding scale factor to 0.

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1705478

+Keeps the filament towards the centre and close to the spool so it is far less likely to jump off the spool.
+Can be fastened to the 2020 with one of the kits spare M5 bolts and T-nuts.
+Can be printed with no support in the default file orientation.
+There is a slit in the circle of the guide so you can slip the filament in without having to cut and reload.
+For optimal results move the spool holder as close to the guide as your filament spool will allow.

There are likely far better fixes out there to this problem, this is by no means foolproof, but it was a quick and easy hack to get the above spool holder working for me without so many filament tangles. This does not guarantee that filament may still not jump off the spool, as it has still occasionally done so for me with very large movements, but most often at the beginning of a print or start of a new spool.

description.text:
Tiny model of an A400M aircraft which can be made into a Christmas ornament. Its quite fiddly to assemble if you wan the propellers to spin.
NOTE: updated with solid wings and tail planes so that they print correctly at this scale.

Assembly instructions

This can be very fiddly if you want the propellers to spin but it is possible with a bit of post printing sanding and drilling.
Firstly glue the FWD fuselage to the AFT fuselage, then glue each wing on (the wings are anhedral so attached at the top of the fuselage and sloping downwards with the holes for the engine attachment underneath). Then glue the vertical tail plane to the rear of the AFT fuselage and the horizontal tail planes on each side ( the flatter side of the horizontal tail plane should be on top, but at this scale there is not really any perceivable difference). Next glue the engines to the wings, the spigot on the engines should insert into the holes in the underside of the wings so you can get them in the correct spot and they should be parallel to the fuselage. Finally the Propellers; if you want, these can just be glued straight onto the engine and the model is complete. Getting them to spin takes quite a bit of work but it can be worth it, I have managed to get them so they spin when you blow on them. You will need to run a very small drill bit down the shaft hole in the engines and smooth out the engine shafts so that they can turn freely in the engine. Then glue the shafts into the propellers and insert them through eh engines. Finally glue the shaft cap onto the back of the shaft being careful not to glue the shaft to the engine itself.
If you wan the model to hang up, you can glue the loop on. I have glued mine on do that it makes the aircraft hang at a climb and bank. The centre of the model is in the centre-line of the fuselage and towards the back of the wing. My models were light enough that I used a small piece of Plasticine to test where I would put the loop to get the hanging effect I was after. Please feel free to ask any questions.
